## How GLQ works
{% if is_trellis %}

A **randomized Hadamard transform** (a fixed random sign-flip + Hadamard rotation on each side) makes the weights and the calibration Hessian *incoherent* — spreading outliers so they quantize well. **LDLQ** then rounds the weights with error feedback across the remaining input dimensions via the Hessian's LDL factorization. Instead of a per-group lattice codebook, GLQ here uses **trellis-coded quantization** (TCQ, from [QTIP](https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.11235)): each 16×16 weight tile is encoded as a **tail-biting Viterbi sequence over a dimension-256 trellis code**, reaching a higher effective quantization dimension than an 8-D lattice at the same bit-rate. Decoding is a small look-up plus a few arithmetic ops per weight; a fused CUDA kernel keeps the weights compressed in VRAM and decodes them inline.

The "Golay/Leech" in the project name refers to the lattice codebooks GLQ also ships (E8 and its higher-dimensional cousins). Code, kernels and quantizer: **[GLQ on GitHub]({{ glq_repo }})**.
{% else %}

GLQ compresses weights in groups of 8. A **randomized Hadamard transform** (a fixed random sign-flip + Hadamard rotation on each side) makes the weights and the calibration Hessian *incoherent* — spreading outliers so an 8-dimensional lattice quantizes them well. **LDLQ** then rounds each group to the nearest entry of an **E8 shell codebook** (a 65,536-point subset of the E8 lattice), feeding each group's rounding error forward across the remaining input dimensions via the Hessian's LDL factorization. {{ stages_blurb }}

E8 is the 8-dimensional root lattice; the "Golay/Leech" in the project name refers to its higher-dimensional lattice cousins. Code, kernels and quantizer: **[GLQ on GitHub]({{ glq_repo }})**.
{% endif %}

